Crimée and Sudetenland, same fight?
BRUSSELS – The Russian takeover of Crimea constitutes the most serious example of aggression in peacetime that Europe has experienced since the annexation of the Sudetenland by Nazi Germany in 1938.
It is certainly now fashionable to downplay the importance of the "Munich lessons" when referring to this episode in which Neville Chamberlain and Édouard Daladier gave in to Hitler's demands on Czechoslovakia in order to appease the Führer.
However, if the Western world were to turn a blind eye to the annexation of Crimea – the second case of invasion of a sovereign territory by Russian President Vladimir Putin, following the takeover of the Georgian regions of Abkhazia and South Ossetia in 2008 – current democratic leaders might very well regret their inaction.
Reactions in Western capitals have so far been mixed.
The sanctions currently being considered – such as expulsion from the G8, for example – could seem trivial if the threat to peace in Europe were not so serious.
Putin considers the collapse of the Soviet Union as the worst catastrophe of the modern era, the man tirelessly striving to revive a fallen Russian empire.
If the West is to be taken seriously, it will have to act with the same determination that Putin demonstrates.
Putin's many successes within the framework of his imperialist project have so far cost him almost nothing.
His initiative in favor of an Eurasian Economic Community has allowed Russia to attract a number of resource-rich states, such as Kazakhstan, Uzbekistan, and Turkmenistan.
Georgia was dismembered in 2008.
As for the Armenian government, Russian intimidation pushed it to reject the association agreement proposed by the European Union.
And here we are, with the most precious geostrategic trophy – Ukraine – likely to fall into Putin’s hands.
Without Ukraine, Russia « ceases to be an empire, » as explains the former U.S. national security advisor Zbigniew Brzezinski; « on the contrary, strong with a suborned and subordinate Ukraine, Russia automatically becomes an empire again. » And since the majority of Ukrainians have no desire to join Putin’s empire, it is highly likely that the country led by the Russian president will now become a highly militarized state, a sort of Soviet Union devoid of a Communist Party.
It is essential that the international community’s response be commensurate with the degree of adventurism demonstrated by Putin.
Cancellation of summits, proposals for trade agreements, and other participation in as unproductive a forum as the G8 could hardly suffice.
Only actions involving the imposition of tangible economic sanctions, likely to affect Russian citizens – who, recall, keep re-electing Putin to power – could allow us to hope that the Kremlin will leave its expansionist path.
What sanctions could this involve?
First, Turkey could decide to close the Dardanelles Strait to Russian transport, as it did after the 2008 Russo-Georgian war.
At the time, Turkey had blocked access to the Black Sea in order to prevent the United States from intervening, although it now clearly appears that this was not the intention of the United States.
Today, Turkey could choose to close the Turkish straits not only to Russian warships, but also to all commercial freighters heading toward Russian ports in the Black Sea.
The impact on Russia's economy – as well as on Putin's military ambitions – would be considerable.
Turkey is authorized to close the Dardanelles under an amendment made in 1982 to the 1936 Montreux Convention.
Turkey could thus turn Putin's own justification for the annexation of Crimea – namely, that he would protect the Russian-speaking ethnicities there – against him by asserting that it is protecting its own Turkic cousins, the Tatars, who, given the mistreatment they have suffered at the hands of Russia, clearly wish to remain under Ukrainian rule.
This week, Turkish Foreign Minister Ahmet Davutoğlu ordered his plane to make a mid-air U-turn in order to head toward Kyiv to support the new interim government.
Prime Minister Recep Tayyip Erdoğan, who as Putin knows is not exactly a softie, could thus follow suit by immediately closing the Turkish straits to Russian transport – until Putin recalls all his troops from Crimea back to their bases, namely those in Sevastopol or Russia.
It would be good for Turkey to be able to count on the guarantee provided by Article 5 of the NATO treaty in the event that Russia attempts to intimidate it.
Secondly, President Barack Obama could impose on Russia the same type of financial sanctions that he imposed on Iran around its nuclear program.
These sanctions have indeed significantly undermined the Iranian economy.
In the same way, refusing access to the US financial system for all banks dealing with Russian banks or companies would generate an unprecedented economic chaos in Russia since the fall of communism.
Russian citizens must understand that allowing Putin – whose rise to power is based on his promise to end the shortages of the early post-Soviet era – to pursue his aggressive imperialist agenda could cost them dearly.
Thirdly, Obama could remind the Chinese of their role in the stability of Eurasia.
To Putin, the disintegration of the Soviet Union was a true tragedy, but for China, it was the most formidable geopolitical opportunity imaginable.
In an instant, this empire that had seized millions of hectares of Chinese territory over the centuries and threatened the People's Republic with nuclear annihilation simply vanished.
Since then, the independent states of Central Asia, and Ukraine itself, have become important trade partners of China.
The Russian invasion of Georgia seriously upset China, as evidenced by its stance at the Shanghai Cooperation Organization summit held after the war (this regional group bringing together a number of post-Soviet states sharing borders with China and the motherland).
Russia tried to get the OCS to recognize the independence of Abkhazia and South Ossetia.
The Organization nevertheless expressed its disagreement.
However, the Central Asian member countries – Kazakhstan, Kyrgyzstan, Tajikistan, and Uzbekistan – could never have risen against the Kremlin without China's support.
It is now up to Chinese President Xi Jinping to be less enigmatic in his response to Putin's audacity.
The real test of this Chinese claim to assert itself as a genuine and responsible protagonist within the international community will indeed take place very soon at the United Nations.
Will China support this blatant violation of international law committed by Putin, or will it stand in support of Ukraine's territorial integrity?
Two other sanction options are also under consideration.
Each Russian leader could thus see their visas rejected or revoked.
It would also be possible to freeze a number of assets, including those that have been laundered by oligarchs close to Putin.
It will only be when the pain becomes unbearable, especially for the elites, that this sort of kampf that Putin is leading today can fail.
The cost of inaction could well be considerable.
Many countries, from Japan to Israel, count on this American promise to act firmly against any serious threat to peace.
Moreover, when Ukraine gave up its nuclear arsenal in 1994, it did so on the condition that the United States (alongside the United Kingdom, France, and Russia) guarantee its territorial integrity.
If Crimea were to remain annexed, no one can blame Ukraine if it decides to re-nuclearize its defense (something it remains technologically capable of doing).
When Chamberlain returned from Munich, Winston Churchill addressed him with the famous phrase "You had the choice between war and dishonor."
You chose dishonor, and you will have war." Obama and other Western leaders are today facing a similar choice.
If they were to choose dishonor, we can be certain that the audacious Putin will eventually serve them another war.
